Review your application's security policy. Identify if your application's security policy has provided the appropriate FilePermission and RuntimePermission entries to allow your application to load the necessary native libraries. The following examples illustrate the permissions necessary for your application to load specific libraries:
      
        
          
            Windows: Loading the library myapp.dll in a Windows environment would require the following permissions:
          grant codeBase "file:e:/myapp/bin/-"{  permission java.io.FilePermission "e:/myapp/lib/myapp.dll", "read";  permission java.lang.RuntimePermission "loadLibrary.myapp";  permission java.util.PropertyPermission "user.dir", "read";};
        
        
          
            Linux: If your application is Linux based, it would require the following permissions to load the library libmyapp.so:
          grant codeBase "file:/myapp/bin/-"{  permission java.io.FilePermission "/myapp/lib/libmyapp.so", "read";  permission java.lang.RuntimePermission "loadLibrary.myapp";  permission java.util.PropertyPermission "user.dir", "read";};

